    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Sound-Sensor">
      <title>Sound Sensor </title>
      <p>
        Sound sensor will detect the sound wave from the microphone attached in the sensor. The sound sensor has its own inbuilt microphone, a peak detector and an amplifier to convert the sound signal to voltage. Microphone will detect the sound generated from any external force, then the sound will be further converted to an operating voltage, then the operating voltage will be sent to micro controller for further execution.  Sensor has three pins D0, +, -.  
      </p>
      <sidebyside valign="middle">
      <figure>
        <image source="/images/sound_sensor.jpg" width="50%"/>
        <caption>Sound Sensor </caption>
      </figure>
            <interactive iframe="https://p.interacty.me/6fb61e926ba7ce4c/iframe.html"/>
      </sidebyside>
       <p><em><term>Arrange the above and below blocks in the frame to complete puzzle"</term></em> </p>

      <p>
        D0 is used as input pin for reading the data, VCC and GND is used as input pins for power supply.  Sound sensor works similarly to the working of human ear that consists of diaphragm. Diaphragm will convert the vibration into digital signal. It is widely used in applications like mobile phones and audio systems. LM393 sound sensor is shown in fig 2.3.2. From table 2.3.3 the pin configuration of the sound sensor is explained with its purpose. Sound sensor has its own variation. The characteristics of the sensor depend on the type of microphones used. There are different types of micro phone i.e.  Carbon micro phone, ribbon microphone, dynamic microphone and condenser micro phone.  LM393 is preferred widely for applications like hearing aid and also for radio and television broadcasting.
      </p>
